snippet.textDisplay:
If Larry Bird is still agitated by Bill Laimbeer after all these years, then Bill Laimbeer accomplished his mission!
As a Pistons fan I watched all the games between The Celtics and Pistons from the mid 80's to the early 90's, and it was GAME ON! A Clash of Titans for Eastern Conference Supremacy!! If you think about it, that steal by Bird in game 5 of the 87 ECF with the game and the series advantage on the line was so smart and calculated by Larry, he made sure The Pistons paid the price for rushing the inbounds. He caught Isiah in a moment that Isiah still regrets to this day.
The Pistons had to learn the hard way from 1987, and give them credit because they had to overcome adversity from the loss in the 88 Finals as well. I'm just glad The Detroit Pistons had the resilience to win Back-to-Back NBA Crowns. A lot lesser teams would have folded up shop, and never been heard from again.
Larry vs. Bill. Boston vs. Detroit. I wouldn't change a thing about it!
snippet.textOriginal:
If Larry Bird is still agitated by Bill Laimbeer after all these years, then Bill Laimbeer accomplished his mission! 
As a Pistons fan I watched all the games between The Celtics and Pistons from the mid 80's to the early 90's, and it was GAME ON! A Clash of Titans for Eastern Conference Supremacy!! If you think about it, that steal by Bird in game 5 of the 87 ECF with the game and the series advantage on the line was so smart and calculated by Larry, he made sure The Pistons paid the price for rushing the inbounds. He caught Isiah in a moment that Isiah still regrets to this day. 
The Pistons had to learn the hard way from 1987, and give them credit because they had to overcome adversity from the loss in the 88 Finals as well. I'm just glad The Detroit Pistons had the resilience to win Back-to-Back NBA Crowns.  A lot lesser teams would have folded up shop, and never been heard from again. 
Larry vs. Bill. Boston vs. Detroit. I wouldn't change a thing about it!

snippet.authorDisplayName: Matthew Joseph The Common Sense American
snippet.textDisplay:
2 of my favorite NBA players of all time. The old time guys played ball like men. Not a fan of today's NBA because it's a bunch of pampered elites bouncing a ball chucking up shots and pirouetting around the court trying not to breath to hard on each other, worried more about their insta feeds than leaving it all out on the court.

Laimbeer and Bird gave everything they had every play and left it all out on the court. True heavyweights who took it to each other each time down the court be it a game in January or the east conference championship. Truly a joy to go back and watch these guys play. There is something to be said watching guys who aren't boys off the court and dislike each other for real locked in a mental and physical battle against each other. LeBron and KD couldn't hold these guys jocks.
